What does â€œtype-safeâ€ mean in Java?

Type safety means:

The compiler ensures that only valid values of a specific type are used in your program.

In other words â€”
you canâ€™t assign or compare invalid values, and the compiler will catch it before runtime.

ðŸ§© Now â€” How is enum Type-Safe?

Letâ€™s compare it with the old way (using constants) vs the enum way.

ðŸ”¹ âŒ Old Way (using static final constants)
public class OldWay {
    public static final int MONDAY = 1;
    public static final int TUESDAY = 2;
    public static final int WEDNESDAY = 3;
}

public class TestOldWay {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int day = 5; // âŒ Invalid value, but compiler wonâ€™t complain!

        if (day == OldWay.MONDAY) {
            System.out.println("Start of week");
        }
    }
}


ðŸ‘‰ Here:

You can assign any integer (like 5, 10, or even -1).

The compiler wonâ€™t give an error.

Youâ€™ll get logical bugs â€” because 5 doesnâ€™t represent any real day.

So, no type safety here. ðŸ˜ž

------------------------------------------------------------
âœ… Enum Way (Type Safe)
enum Day {
    MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY
}

public class TestEnum {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Day day = Day.MONDAY; // âœ… Only valid values allowed

        // âŒ Compiler error if you try:
        // day = 5;         // Error: incompatible types
        // day = null;      // Error unless explicitly allowed
    }
}


âœ… Explanation:

day is of type Day.

It can only hold one of the defined constants (MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY).

If you try to assign anything else, the compiler will show an error immediately.

Thatâ€™s why enums are type-safe.


